data.title: A bit of everything!
data.text: The upstairs has a bit of everything, books,postcards, period clothing, glassware, and much, much more. I read the negative reviews and guess those people never made it past the first floor which also houses many interesting items, however, the bulk of the items are located on the second floor.

data.title: Short Visit
data.text: Was excited to go here. Not looking for anything specific. Felt that the prices were quite high. Quite an abundance of animals and dishes. Didn't make it to the other floors. Lost interest.

data.title: Great place to wander and relive days gone by
data.text: Wonderful spot to spend a day wandering and searching for a treasure.  Fantastic spot to have things framed in a quality antique frame.  Three floors of amazing finds.  Good prices for the most part as well.

data.title: A must place to stop and browse!
data.text:
This is a must for all antique lovers! The historic building adds a wonderful feel. This was a old tire factory converted into many artist and antique shops
Pp

data.title: Kind of a dud
data.text: Lots of off-the-wall stuff to look at and the building is really interesting. But we really didn't find anything to buy here, which is unusual for an antique mall visit. We hoped for a better variety of goods given the size. Instead, we saw dozens of taxidermy wall mounts, piles of old magazines and books, glassware, and furniture. Meh.

data.title: All the things you didn't know you needed....
data.text: For an enjoyable afternoon, try visiting this unique eclectic building in downtown Eau Claire. The building itself is one of the older ones left and it was for many years a furniture store. It has a creaky but dependable elevator which can take you up to the spooky third floor where you can explore to your hearts content all the larger old furniture items that gather dust of the ages. This place is loaded with aisles of books/postcards/art - they have statuary, taxidermy and everything in between. Many items are obviously left overs from huge estates. I have found many smaller items that still grace our home - just unusual little things such as gorgeous little clocks, ivory-toned pictures and interesting metal birds that are so realistic. They have collections from WWII, jewelry, coins and all the bric-a-brac you need to set up your mid-century memory room. This is a place you will likely not want to bring your children along to enjoy - there's just too much "stuff" and it's overwhelming enough for adults. Plus, who wants to pay for broken Limoges? Eau Claire is lucky to have this quaint, peculiar and delightful business.

data.title: Loads of stuff!
data.text: If you're looking for something, anything, you'll probably find it here!  They have everything from old advertisements to vintage music to clothing.  Some of the books had a very moldy smell, but overall, there was some really cool vintage items!

data.title: Antique/Curio shop
data.text: I have been going to the emporium for many years, I can't imagine what a first timer must think. There is an extensive taxidermy collection with many exotics including a full hyena, kudu, wildebeest, and a set of elephant ears, and of course a two-headed calf. Their selection is large, encompassing three floors in an aged building that was originally a Masonic Temple. I would recommend it to any and all for shopping and exploring. Do try to find the authentic human skeleton, $1200 seems reasonable......doesn't it?

data.title: Old Stuff
data.text: Lots of old stuff.  Smells old.  Not much for the average consumer to buy but there are many interesting things to look at.

data.title: Fun Place to Explore!
data.text: You never know what you might find! Part of a clarinet, a human skeleton, cute hats, bizarre artwork, or ostrich taxidermy, it's all here. For better, or for worse. I honestly want to make a scavenger hunt out of the Antique Emporium for others to use when they visit because I think it would be fun. In all seriousness though, there is a lot of good finds here. Happy browsing!
